x.max <- max(sapply(sapply(sim, time_bins), max))
y.max <- 1.05 * max(sapply(sapply(sim, function(x) median(x)[["NI"]]), max, na.rm=TRUE))

plot(time_bins(sim$er), median(sim$er)[["NI"]], type="l", lwd=2, col="blue", xlim=c(0, x.max), ylim=c(0, 100), xlab="Time", ylab=expression(N[I](t)))
lines(time_bins(sim$ba), median(sim$ba)[["NI"]], lwd=2, col="gold")
lines(time_bins(sim$ws), median(sim$ws)[["NI"]],lwd=2, col="red")
legend("topright", c("ER", "BA", "WS"),col=c("blue", "gold", "red"), lty=1)

You need to plot three values on the graphics: Number of infected, number of suseprible, number of recovered - all depends on time. As a result of this task, you need to provide 12 plots (one for each network with 3 diferent parameters) with explanation.

Number of infected, number of susceptible, number of recovered - all depends on time.

The main ideas of these models are: - Erdos-Renyi (ER) model: every possible edge is created with the same constant probability. - Barabasi-Albert (BA) model: each new node is connected to existing nodes with a probability proportional to the number of links of these nodes. - Watts-Strogatz (WS) model: accounts for clustering while retaining the short average path lengths of the ER model.

At the plots we see that as time increases, we get that r(t) (fraction of the population that will get sick) stabilizes and so dr/dt = 0 and lines come to 0 - common thing for all the simulations.

At the given simulation (2 4 100) for er model we see the peak, but rather small.

for ba model we see the bigger peak relatively to other plots

for ws model we dont see peaks - this connected with the fact that only 1 cluster for this model exists (see the result of function no.clusters(gl$ws)).

At the given simulation (8 2 1000) because of a big value of beta parameter and small value of gamma we see the highest peaks of all the simulations and the typical coming to 0 for all the models. It connected with the formulas (ds/ dt = - beta * s * x and dx/dt = beta * s * x - gamma * x) - the big increment at the time.
